      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Local Pack, Google 3-Pack</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Map Pack</strong> is the block of 3 local business listings — with an embedded Google Map — that appears at the top of search results for queries with local intent ("dentist near me," "best pizza Chicago"). Also called the Local Pack or Google 3-Pack. According to BrightLocal's 2023 survey, <strong>42% of local searchers click results within the Map Pack</strong>, making it the most valuable position in local SEO for most businesses.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Click share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">42% of local searches</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Listings shown</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3 (standard)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Ranking in the top 3 organic results is hard. Ranking in the Map Pack for local searches is a separate, parallel competition with its own ranking factors — and for businesses with a physical location or local service area, it's often the higher-ROI target.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Map Pack?</h2>
        <p>The Map Pack is a Google SERP feature triggered by local intent. It displays:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Business name, category, and Google Business Profile rating</li>
          <li>Star rating and review count</li>
          <li>Address and distance from the searcher</li>
          <li>Operating hours (open/closed indicator)</li>
          <li>Phone number (click-to-call on mobile)</li>
          <li>Directions link</li>
          <li>Brief description or service highlights (from GBP)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>On mobile, the Map Pack fills the screen above the fold — users often never scroll to organic results. This concentration of high-intent local traffic in a small set of listings is why Map Pack competition is intense in most service categories.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">BrightLocal 2023 Local Consumer Review Survey</div>
          <p>42% of local searchers click on Map Pack results. Businesses with 100+ photos on Google Business Profile receive <strong>520% more calls</strong> than the average GBP listing. Reviews are the most-read factor before visiting a local business — 98% of consumers read them.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the Map Pack matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Four concrete reasons every local business needs a Map Pack strategy:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Click concentration.</strong> 42% of local search clicks go to Map Pack results. Organic position 1 for the same query typically gets 28-32% of clicks. The Map Pack is the first choice for local searchers.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile dominance.</strong> On mobile, the Map Pack fills the entire screen. For queries like "plumber near me" searched on a phone during an emergency, the Map Pack is effectively the entire result.</li>
          <li><strong>Built-in conversion features.</strong> Integrated call buttons, directions links, and review displays reduce friction from search to contact. Users don't need to visit your website to call you.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust signals at a glance.</strong> A Map Pack listing with 200 reviews and a 4.8-star rating builds trust before the click. This pre-qualifies interest and improves call and visit quality, not just volume.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google determines Map Pack rankings</h2>
        <p>Google uses three primary factors to rank Map Pack results — and all three must be addressed simultaneously for sustained placement.</p>

        <h3>1. Relevance</h3>
        <p>How well does the business match what the searcher is looking for? Signals include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Primary and secondary GBP business categories</li>
          <li>Business description keywords</li>
          <li>Services listed in GBP</li>
          <li>Website content matching the search query</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Distance</h3>
        <p>How close is the business to the searcher (or the location specified in the query)? Google uses IP address and GPS data to determine location. This factor is mostly outside your control — but businesses with multiple locations or service areas can optimise by creating location-specific landing pages and GBP profiles for each.</p>

        <h3>3. Prominence</h3>
        <p>How well-known and reputable is the business? Signals include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Number and recency of Google reviews</li>
          <li>Star rating (average and distribution)</li>
          <li>Citation volume and consistency (NAP across directories)</li>
          <li>Backlinks to the business website</li>
          <li>GBP post frequency and photo volume</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Map Pack variations — what Google shows</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Variation</th><th>When it appears</th><th>Listings shown</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Standard 3-Pack</strong></td><td>Most local service queries</td><td>3 businesses + map</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Teaser Pack</strong></td><td>Restaurants, hotels — shows photos/menus</td><td>3 businesses with rich snippets</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local Services Ads Pack</strong></td><td>Google-vetted service categories</td><td>2-3 paid listings above Map Pack</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Map Pack with Justifications</strong></td><td>Queries with specific terms (e.g. "open now")</td><td>3 businesses with highlighted attribute</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local Finder</strong></td><td>After clicking "More places"</td><td>20+ businesses on expanded map</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Map Pack examples and outcomes</h2>

        <h3>1. Medical practice — review programme</h3>
        <p>A medical practice (Dr Martinez example) implemented a systematic post-visit review request process targeting 4-8 new reviews per month. Within 90 days, Map Pack placement for core service queries drove 35 new patient calls per month — calls that did not exist before the review programme began.</p>

        <h3>2. Home services — citation audit</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company with inconsistent NAP (Name, Address, Phone) across directories — some showing old suite numbers, some missing the phone extension — resolved all inconsistencies through a citation audit. Within 60 days, Map Pack rankings improved for 12 of their 20 primary local keywords.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Map Pack vs local organic results — which to prioritise</h2>
        <p>Most local businesses should prioritise the Map Pack first, then local organic. Here's why.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Map Pack (prioritise first)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>42% of local search clicks</li>
              <li>Appears above all organic results</li>
              <li>Built-in call and directions buttons</li>
              <li>Reviews visible before the click</li>
              <li>Accessible to any business, no website required</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Local organic (important for complete coverage)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No follower or review requirement</li>
              <li>Strong for informational local queries</li>
              <li>Builds long-term domain authority</li>
              <li>Captures searchers who scroll past Map Pack</li>
              <li>Amplifies Map Pack prominence signals</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices to rank in the Map Pack</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Select the most specific primary GBP category.</strong> "Plumber" outperforms "Contractor" for plumbing searches. The primary category is the single highest-weight relevance signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Build 4-8 new reviews monthly.</strong> Review velocity — the rate of new reviews — matters as much as total count. A consistent monthly cadence outperforms a one-time campaign that stops.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Response rate and response recency are ranking signals. Respond within 48 hours, including negative reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit NAP consistency across all directories.</strong> Inconsistent business name, address, or phone number across Yelp, Bing Places, Apple Maps, and industry directories reduces prominence scores.</li>
          <li><strong>Post to GBP weekly.</strong> GBP Posts keep the listing active and signal to Google that the business is engaged. Use Posts for promotions, events, and new services.</li>
          <li><strong>Upload 100+ photos.</strong> Businesses with 100+ photos receive 520% more calls than average. Category photos, team photos, and service photos all contribute.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local landing pages on your website.</strong> For each service area or location, create a dedicated page with consistent NAP, local keywords, and embedded Google Maps. These support the Prominence signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor your GBP for spam edits.</strong> Competitors and bots sometimes edit GBP listings. Set up alerts in Search Console and check your listing weekly for unauthorised changes.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — keyword-stuffing the business name</div>
          <p>Adding keywords to your Google Business Profile name ("Joe's Plumbing - Best Plumber Denver") violates Google's guidelines and can result in your GBP being suspended or your name reverted. Use your legal business name only. Your ranking for relevant keywords comes from categories, services, and reviews — not your business name field.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Map Pack mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring review velocity</strong> — 200 reviews from 3 years ago beats 50 reviews from last month. But 50 reviews this month beats 200 old reviews in most algorithms. Keep it active.</li>
          <li><strong>Incomplete GBP profiles</strong> — missing hours, services, photos, or business description leaves relevance signals on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Not using GBP services and products sections</strong> — these sections match your listing to specific service queries and are frequently underused.</li>
          <li><strong>Building citations without auditing existing ones</strong> — adding new citations while old incorrect ones still exist creates inconsistency that reduces rather than improves prominence.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting the website</strong> — GBP optimisation without a strong linked website has diminishing returns. Prominence is partly determined by your site's authority and local relevance.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many businesses appear in the Map Pack?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
